column5:
Assess the risk exposure of gaps identified in:
 (a) the procurement process; 
 (b) ongoing contract management of sampled suppliers.

Consideration should be given to the following actions for each business area: 
 Develop a Business-as-usual process and/or policy for obtaining legal and compliance sign-offs in the marketing asset lifecycle which includes the following: 
 Roles and responsibilities; 
 Streamlining the internal handovers for obtaining approvals with due consideration to local volumes, multiple touchpoints and/or interdependencies on local vs global campaigns.
 Categories of marketing collateral requiring legal and compliance sign-off and those which are an exception; e.g. internal pre-approved content such as social media - cultural moments and the establishment of an external portal for pre-approved content for all Merchants;
 Induction training sharing content related to sign-off process, Legal Marketing Guidelines and the systems for obtaining feedback and approvals at local levels; 
 Maintaining awareness through periodic reminders e.g. Comms, refresher training.

To implement within EU Clearpay websites for Spain, France and Italy:
 - Banner and preference setting;
 - Provide code for “manage cookies” button when EU Cookies Notice migrates to Builder platform, and for the Afterpay Cookies Notice

LERT management will update the RFPA SOPs to align with the current RFPA policy, including:


 •While the minimum required information is already maintained for each request, the SOP will be updated to reflect this requirement (i.e., date of the request, name of the government authority, identification of the records disclosed); 
 •The RFPA applicability requirements will be described in the SOP (i.e., come from the federal government, apply to an individual person or a partnership with five or fewer people, seek confidential financial information);
 •The SOP will describe records applicable to SFS that do not qualify as a protected record ( i.e., records relating to an account established under a fictitious name); and 
 •The RFPA DRI Arvon Perteet will be removed and updated.

The firm will implement the following KPIs:
 % of clients onboarded in a week; 
 % of screening alerts closed within 1 day; 
 % of SARs investigated following an internal SAR within 10 days;
 % of transaction monitoring alerts investigated within 30 days;
 % of high risk clients; 
 % of high-risk MCCs;
 % of Sellers with adverse media / enforcement alerts; 
 % alerts triggered for ongoing monitoring review.

MAP 1: Block will conduct a comprehensive analysis to assess whether any amendments should be made to its existing sanctions keyword list. The analysis will include:
 A review of active sanctions programs, including Russia as well as sanctions programs unrelated to Russia (e.g.: Iran, Belarus, Cuba), to potentially identify terms and keyword combinations for inclusion;
 A review of transactions resulting in block or reject reports to identify potential trends/common terms indicative of a sanctions nexus;
 A review of a sample of historically productive terms and assessment of the materiality of the corresponding alerts; 
 Testing of proposed additional terms against historical keyword data to assess the expected productivity and materiality of adding the terms; and
 Benchmarking proposal through external Sanctions Regulatory Counsel for informal/verbal guidance.

To address any outstanding deficiencies in Block’s transaction monitoring and sanctions filtering programs that may be associated with the New York Department of Financial Service’s findings in the April 10, 2025 Consent Order, Block will review and update its framework and thresholds for its blockchain analytics vendors as follows:
 1. Ensure a risk-based framework for establishing and updating vendor thresholds for certain actions (e.g. detection, prevention, blocking), inclusive of transactional and counterparty risk (e.g. mixers), supported by documented rationale and governance;
 2. Formalize the establishment of thresholds for its vendor-provided monitoring that are supported by risk-based analysis, inclusive of scenario tuning and testing;
 3. Updating relevant policies and procedures to ensure on-going compliance with applicable New York and federal anti-money laundering and OFAC regulations and alignment with NYDFS guidance on the Use of Blockchain Analytics (April 28, 2022);
 4. Create internal controls to ensure thresholds are revisited on an ongoing basis.

To address any outstanding deficiencies in Block’s transaction monitoring and sanctions filtering programs that may be associated with the New York Department of Financial Service’s findings in the April 10, 2025 Consent Order, Block will review and update its framework and thresholds for its blockchain analytics vendors as follows:
 1. Ensure a risk-based framework for establishing and updating vendor thresholds for certain actions (e.g. detection, prevention, blocking), inclusive of transactional and counterparty risk (e.g. mixers), supported by documented rationale and governance;
 2. Formalize the establishment of thresholds for its vendor-provided monitoring that are supported by risk-based analysis, inclusive of scenario tuning and testing;
 3. Updating relevant policies and procedures to ensure on-going compliance with applicable New York and federal anti-money laundering and OFAC regulations and alignment with NYDFS guidance on the Use of Blockchain Analytics (April 28, 2022);
 4. Create internal controls to ensure thresholds are revisited on an ongoing basis.

To address any outstanding deficiencies in Block’s transaction monitoring that may be associated with findings related to anonymizing services aka “mixers” (“Mixers”) in the Department’s April 10, 2025 Consent Order related to the NYDFS review of Block’s Cash App BTC Sanctions and AML Transaction Program, Block will:
 1. Review existing controls and risk ratings related to Mixers, which were reviewed with the Department’s supervisory team in December 2023, to evaluate whether any additional risk-based measures are appropriate.  
 2. Updating relevant policies and procedures to ensure on-going compliance with applicable BSA and OFAC regulations and alignment with NYDFS guidance on the Use of Blockchain Analytics (April 28, 2022);

